distinction still more clearly. “Fallaciae in dictione sunt illae penos quas secundum omnes modos peccant sophistica argumenta composita ex signis voluntarie institutis. Fallaciae extra dictionem sunt illae penes quas peccant argumenta tam composita ex signis voluntarie institutis quam composita ex signis naturaliter significantibus.” Logica, iii. 4. cap. 1. The former arise from defects in the arbitrary signs of thought, and hence are frequently confined to a single language. The latter are in the thought itself, whether materially, in the falso application of notions to things, or formassy, in the violation os the laws by which the operatione of the reason should be governed. Under this head are thus included both salse judgments and illogical reasonings. These Fallacies are connected with language only secondarily and accidentally; the former primarily and essentially.
